  "opinion": "As a 19-year-old woman growing up in Philadelphia with parents who both have advanced education—one with a PhD and the other with an upper secondary degree—I’ve seen firsthand how stereotype threat can quietly shape experiences in STEM fields. Stereotype threat isn’t just a theory; it’s the weight of being perceived as less capable because of your gender, race, or background. For example, when I took my first calculus class in high school, I noticed how my male classmates seemed more confident in their problem-solving, while I found myself second-guessing my answers. This isn’t about individual ability—it’s about the invisible pressure of being labeled as 'not one of us' in a space that’s often dominated by men. As someone who’s deeply curious about science and technology but also aware of how societal biases can affect learning, I believe we absolutely must address stereotype threat in STEM. The solution isn’t just about fixing individual classrooms but creating systemic change through inclusive teaching practices, mentorship programs, and representation in media. In my community, I’ve seen how organizations like Girls Who Code and local universities hosting workshops for underrepresented students help break down these barriers. It’s crucial to normalize conversations about bias and empower students to see themselves as part of the STEM narrative, not as exceptions to it. By doing this, we can build a future where everyone, regardless of background, feels welcome and capable in these fields.",
